Telco Churn Kaggle Dataset: Analysis with FastAI Workflow¶

Preamble¶

This data is from IBM's collection of sample data, and represents data about a number of customers from a telecom company. The goal is to predict customer churn based on the customer data provided.

Each row represents a customer, each column contains customers attributes described on the column Metadata. The raw data contains 7043 rows (customers) and 21 columns (features). The Churn column is our target.

Note: This analysis follows the workflow described in the FastAI ML course, using random forests to both predict the outcome and analyze feature importance.

Examining the Data¶

Loading in the dataset¶

Before we can do anything we should load in the data from the .csv that contains it.

In [1]:
%load_ext autoreload
%autoreload 2
%matplotlib inline

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

df_raw = pd.read_csv('WA_Fn-UseC_-Telco-Customer-Churn.csv')

Looking at raw data and summary statistics¶

It's crucial that we take a look at the data to understand what it looks like before we start to do anything with it. We should also not do anything to it in this step, as we don't want to influence the analysis down the road with our biases. It's better to let the model take care of removing irrelevant details, and to identify potential sources of data leakage, unless we're sure that something in our data represents something unavailable at prediction time in the real world.

From this we can notice a few things. The first is that customerID is most likely not a useful column for the prediction, as it might be a randomly-generated ID that has no bearing on whether or not a customer will leave. However, we can leave it in as random forests will automatically disregard unimportant features.

The second thing we notice is that TotalCharges appears to be a numerical column, but pandas is treating it as object for some reason. Also, there are no null rows.

Thirdly, SeniorCitizen is being treated as a numerical column of type int64, but we can see it simply contains a boolean value of 0 or 1 depending on whether the customer is a SeniorCitizen or not. We should convert this back to a categorical variable, with levels Yes and No for human readability, then when we process the entire dataframe it will be transformed under the hood back into 0s and 1s.

Preparing data for random forest classification¶

Dealing with TotalCharges¶

Since there are no null rows found by pandas in the TotalCharges column, one thing we can do is look for any rows that contain whitespace characters, which would get interpreted as strings and force the entire column to be coerced to object type.

In [6]:
cols =  pd.DataFrame({col_name : sum([int(str(elem).isspace() == True) \
                                 for elem in col]) for col_name, col in df_raw.iteritems()}, index=[0])

The main thing to notice that these rows have in common is that none of these customers have churned, and they all have a tenure of 0, indicating that they have not been with the company for one month yet. Now we can infer that TotalCharges is blank because they have not been charged anything yet as a result of not being around for a month yet. We could remove these rows, but knowing this I think it makes more sense to replace the TotalCharges with 0 and keep them in.

In [8]:
df_raw['TotalCharges'].replace(r'^\s+$', 0, regex=True, inplace=True)
df_raw['TotalCharges'] = df_raw['TotalCharges'].astype('float64')

Converting object columns into categories¶

Our categorical variables are still encoded as strings, which is both inefficient in terms of space and more importantly not in the form that can be used by a random forest. As such, we can encode our categorical variables as pandas categories, which are stored as integers under the hood but still retain their string values when they're examined with functions like describe().

In [11]:
from pandas.api.types import is_numeric_dtype
for n,c in df_raw.items():
    if not is_numeric_dtype(c):
        df_raw[n] = (c.astype('category').cat.as_ordered()).cat.codes

Saving our dataframe in feather format¶

We now have the final version of our dataframe that we'll use for our analysis of feature importance and for training and validating our classifier at the end. We can use the pandas DataFrame.to_feather() to save our data in a format that can very rapidly be read back into memory if we need to load it again. Before we can do that though, we need to reset the index of the dataframe, because to_feather does not support non-default indexes, and since we resampled the data the index is non-default. We can save away that index if we wish to keep it for whatever reason.

In [13]:
# df_index = df_raw.index
# df_raw.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
df_raw.to_feather('telco_churn_raw')

Creating training, validation, and test sets¶

Now we'll split our data into training, validation, and test sets. First we should shuffle our data.

In [14]:
def split_vals(a,n): 
    return a[:n].copy(), a[n:].copy()

# Shuffle the dataframe in place by taking a random sample with the same size as the original dataset

df_train, df_test = split_vals(df_raw, 5500)

Upsampling the positive "Churn" instances to even out the target distribution¶

In [17]:
df_train.groupby('Churn').size()
Out[17]:
Churn
0    4052
1    1448
dtype: int64

We have approximately one churn instance to every three no churn instances. To even out the target distribution and avoid overpredicting no churn due to our imbalanced dataset, we use bootstrap resampling to upsample the minority class to get an even target distribution between "Churn" and "No churn" groups.

To do this, we split the dataset according to the target and then resample the minority class to be the same size as the majority class, then combine the two to form a new, balanced training set.

In [18]:
df_no = df_train[df_train['Churn'] == 0]
df_yes = df_train[df_train['Churn'] == 1]
from sklearn.utils import resample
df_yes_ups = resample(df_yes, replace=True, n_samples=len(df_no))
df_train = pd.concat([df_yes_ups, df_no])
df_train.Churn.value_counts()
Out[18]:
1    4052
0    4052
Name: Churn, dtype: int64

Now we can split this training set dataframe into independent and dependent variables and proceed with our analysis.

In [19]:
X_train, y_train = df_train.drop('Churn', axis=1), df_train['Churn']

Analyzing feature importance with random forests¶

Training our first random forest¶

Now that we have our training, validation, and test sets, we can move on to create a simple random forest classifier to get a sense of how well we can do without much parameter tuning, and be able to move on to the feature importance analysis.

In [20]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

m = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=60, min_samples_leaf=5, max_features=0.5, n_jobs=-1, oob_score=True)
m.fit(X_train, y_train)

def print_score(m):
    res = [m.score(X_train, y_train), m.score(X_val, y_val), m.oob_score_]
    print(res)
    
print_score(m)

[0.9463228035538006, 0.7898832684824902, 0.8667324777887463]

We can see that our first attempt is heavily overfitting to the training data.

Using subsampling to reduce overfitting¶

One way to reduce overfitting and also reduce training time is to use the FastAI function set_rf_samples(), which will allow each of the trees to train on a different subsample of the training dataset we give it, such that overall the trees together will see the entire training set, but individually only see part of it.

In [22]:
from sklearn.ensemble import forest

def set_rf_samples(n):
    """ Changes Scikit learn's random forests to give each tree a random sample of
    n random rows.
    """
    forest._generate_sample_indices = (lambda rs, n_samples:
        forest.check_random_state(rs).randint(0, n_samples, n))
In [23]:
set_rf_samples(1500)
In [24]:
m = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=40, min_samples_leaf=1, max_features='sqrt', n_jobs=-1, oob_score=True)
m.fit(X_train, y_train)
print_score(m)

[0.9016535044422508, 0.7782101167315175, 0.8435340572556762]

Tuning the parameters with GridSearchCV¶

We can try and rectify this overfitting using a grid search to search for better parameters for our model.

In [25]:
params = {
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 3, 5, 10, 25, 100],
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', 0.5, 1]
}

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=40, oob_score=True)
grid = GridSearchCV(rf, param_grid=params, scoring='f1', n_jobs=-1)
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# From the fastai library
def rf_feat_importance(m, df):
    return pd.DataFrame({'cols':df.columns, 'imp':m.feature_importances_}
                       ).sort_values('imp', ascending=False)

Removing redundant features with hierarchical clustering¶

We can see that some of these features are likely related to one another, and so we can try removing some of them to see if our performance improves and if our feature importance makes more sense. Right now we can see MonthlyCharges, TotalCharges, and tenure are dominating nearly 50% of the feature importance, but TotalCharges is really highly correlated with MonthlyCharges and tenure, since it's really the product of those two plus or minus some discrepancy.

In [30]:
import scipy
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.cluster import hierarchy as hc

corr = np.round(scipy.stats.spearmanr(X_train).correlation, 4)
corr_condensed = hc.distance.squareform(1-corr)
z = hc.linkage(corr_condensed, method='average')
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
dendrogram = hc.dendrogram(z, labels=X_train.columns, orientation='left', leaf_font_size=16)
plt.show()

As we can see from the hierarchical clustering, TotalCharges and tenure are very closely correlated, and so we should probably remove TotalCharges to remove a source of collinearity in the model.

Contract is also closely related, which is interesting, since it suggests that the tenure with a company does depend heavily on whether they're on a month-to-month, one-year or two-year contract. This is worth exploring in further detail.

Not surprisingly, Dependents and Partner are also correlated, which makes sense considering that people who have kids often have a partner they had kids with.

Partial dependence plots¶

One way to examine the effects of some of these variables on the Churn outcome is to do some pairwise plots. These have the limitation, however, of potentially showing effects that are produced by other variables, leading to false conclusions about the relationship between the independent and dependent variables.

We can avoid this by using something called a partial dependence plot, where we set the values in a particular column all to the same level, then see what the predictions would look like with all other variables kept equal.

In [34]:
from pdpbox import pdp

def plot_pdp(feat, clusters=None, feat_name=None):
    feat_name = feat_name or feat
    p = pdp.pdp_isolate(m, X_train, list(X_train), feat)
    return pdp.pdp_plot(p, feat_name, plot_lines=True, 
                        cluster=clusters is not None, n_cluster_centers=clusters)

Training the final model¶

Now we're ready to put our model to the test and train it using the parameters we found using our grid search. We can combine training and validation sets so that we have all the data to evaluate on the test set. We should also use a larger number of trees to eke out the last bit of performance.
